<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="play">
<PB REF="4">
<HEAD>LODOISKA.</HEAD>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="act">
<HEAD>ACT I. OVERTURE.</HEAD>
<STAGE>The Act begins towards &s;un-&s;et; the Scene lies upon the borders of Poland, and repre&s;ents a moated ca&s;tle in the Fore&s;t of O&s;tropol.</STAGE>
<STAGE>CHORUS of TARTARS.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ITHORAK&mdash;KHOR.</SPEAKER>
<L>Let's advance; we &s;ee no danger,</L>
<L>All around is hu&s;h as night.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JAPHIS and other TARTARS.</SPEAKER>
<L>To each heart pale fear's a &s;tranger,</L>
<L>Honour bids us to the fight.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>KERA KHAN, KAJAH, TAMURI, CAMAZIN, and The re&s;t of the TARTARS.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>CHORUS&mdash;HORDE.</STAGE>
<L>Kera Khan, whene'er you head us,</L>
<L>Dauntle&s;s to the charge we go;</L>
<L>Gallant chief, then in&s;tant lead us</L>
<L>On to conque&s;t, and our foe.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="6" REF="5">
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here, my friends, here &s;tands the ca&s;tle of Lovin&s;ki.&mdash;This cruel Polander is the &s;courge of his own little territory, and a devouring plague to our Tartar tribes; but the hour of retri|bution is at hand.&mdash;We are too few to &s;torm it now; to-morrow's dawn&mdash;I lo&s;e time.&mdash;Attend; line all the outlets of the fore&s;t, and &s;eize on every pa&s;&s;enger you meet with; but, I command you, &s;pare the lives of tho&s;e who fall into your hands.&mdash;Remem|ber, my brave comrades, the innocent &s;hould ne|ver &s;uffer for the guilty, nor mu&s;t we purcha&s;e our revenge at the price of ju&s;tice and humanity.&mdash; To your po&s;ts;&mdash;begone.</P>
<STAGE>[<HI>Exeunt all the Tartars, except</HI> Kera Khan <HI>and</HI> Ithorak.]</STAGE>
<P>The day declines apace; much is to be done before morning.&mdash;No &s;tragglers to give information!&mdash;no watch upon the towers!&mdash;the ramparts naked!&mdash;Is this fear or de|&s;ign?&mdash;No matter which.&mdash;Come, let us examine farther the &s;ituation of this devoted fortre&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exeunt</STAGE>
<STAGE>Enter COUNT FLORESKI.</STAGE>
<SP>
<Q><TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>AIR.</HEAD>
<L>Lodoi&s;ka, wide over the world</L>
<L>I'll roam, till I find thee, my Fair;</L>
<L>Thy charms &s;hall bani&s;h</L>
<L>Cold de&s;pair:</L>
<L>Love's torch &s;hall illume</L>
<L>The de&s;ert's thick gloom,</L>
<L>And guide with cheering ray</L>
<L>Thy pilgrim's doubtful way.</L>
<L><PB N="7" REF="6">
But, alas!</L>
<L>Should cruel de&s;tiny ordain,</L>
<L>That our true love</L>
<L>Mu&s;t haple&s;s prove,</L>
<L>And we are ne'er to meet again;</L>
<L>It's malice I'll defy,</L>
<L>And for my Lodoi&s;ka die.</L>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter VARBEL, with a Portmantua.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Va&s;tly well, Sir, va&s;tly well; you &s;eem in tip top &s;pirits; &s;ing away, &s;ing away. I told you I &s;aw the Portmantua fall; but the Tartars have gallop'd clear off with the poor bea&s;ts; I thought them as &s;afe grazing there, as if they had been in our own &s;tables.&mdash;Well, we have mi&s;s'd the road to the village, and here we are, wand'ring on foot, in the heart of the fore&s;t of O&s;tropol.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>It was your fault, that they di&s;covered the hor&s;es.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, and it was my fault too, that they did not di&s;cover us.&mdash;A hou&s;e!&mdash;then all my fears are over. I thought we &s;hould never have found an end to this black wood; and, to tell you the truth, I had made up my mind to the comfortable pro&s;|pect of pa&s;&s;ing the night in the arms of one of the bears that were howling about us.&mdash;Won't you go in, Sir?&mdash;though I &s;ee nobody there to open the door to us.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall gain no intelligence in this &s;eque&s;|tered corner. I don't know what to do.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB REF="7">
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know what you &s;hould not have done; you &s;houldn't have giv'n your vote to a candidate, who was oppos'd by your mi&s;tre&s;s's proud father.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not given it?&mdash;Called to the election o<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> a king, honour exacted the performance of my promi&s;e; my friend obtain'd the crown of Poland; I di&s;charged my duty to my country; and we &s;hould hold every &s;acrifice cheap, to maintain a good man on a throne.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very true, Sir; but, all of a &s;udden, you &s;eem to forget, that, for that very rea&s;on, prince Lupau&s;ki has di&s;charged him&s;elf of his promi&s;e to give you his daughter Lodoi&s;ka.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Cruel father! Why &s;o my&s;teriou&s;ly con|ceal the place of her retreat?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>But, dear Sir, con&s;ider, &s;he can't be con|ceal'd for ever. Now wou'dn't it be more natural to get back to War&s;aw as fa&s;t as we can, and wait there, 'till her father &s;ends for the prince&s;s home again? It mu&s;t happen &s;ooner or later. That's certainly the be&s;t way ; and, for my part, I won't budge a &s;tep further for all the Lodoi&s;kas in Chri&s;tendom.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is this your regard, your fidelity? Come on this moment, or&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, recollect, we have fa&s;ted all day: I can't live upon love, if you can; I am almo&s;t &s;tarv'd, and I mu&s;t eat.&mdash;I did not fetch the port|mantean for nothing.&mdash;I can't &s;tir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Wretch! you are for ever embittering
<PB N="9" REF="8">my griefs with your upbraidings!&mdash;Why wou'd you follow me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why?&mdash;why wou'd I follow you? Why, becau&s;e my heart got the better of my head, and made me re&s;olve, in &s;pite of common &s;en&s;e, to ac|company your &s;earch, that I might carry half the load of your griefs for you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Forgive me, my true fellow.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, don't be melancholy; I won't eat, if you don't like it.&mdash;I mu&s;t try to divert him, &mdash;It's I that have mo&s;t cau&s;e to be out of &s;pirits; every thing going on &s;o &s;mooth with the old prince, the happy morning fix'd with the young prince&s;s; &mdash;there was I practi&s;ing how to behave my&s;elf, as ma&s;ter of the ceremonies, among the mu&s;icians, &s;ingers, dancers, lords and ladies, on your wedding day.</P>
<Q><TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>SONG</HEAD>
<LG N="1">
<HEAD>I.</HEAD>
<L>Hark! hark! the mu&s;ic&mdash;</L>
<L>Oh! charming dinning!</L>
<L>The gue&s;ts are &s;eated,</L>
<L>They're all beginning</L>
<L>With the dancing fiddle,</L>
<L>Shrill-&s;queaking hautboy,</L>
<L>The tinkling harp too,</L>
<L>Soft am'rous &s;lute, &s;ir,</L>
<L>The lively trumpet,</L>
<L>The drum &s;o angry,</L>
<L><PB N="10" REF="9">
The bells &s;o merry,</L>
<L>The buzzing cymbal,</L>
<L>The grumbling ba&s;&s;o&mdash;</L>
<L>And the&s;e delights I've lo&s;t</L>
<L>By your wedding's being cro&s;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2">
<HEAD>II.</HEAD>
<L>Look, look around, &s;ir,</L>
<L>The grave ones bridle,</L>
<L>The youths all noddle,</L>
<L>The maidens &s;idle</L>
<L>To the dancing fiddle,</L>
<L>Shrill-&s;queaking hautboy,</L>
<L>The tinkling harp too,</L>
<L>Soft am'rous flute, &s;ir,</L>
<L>And lively trumpet,</L>
<L>The drum &s;o angry,</L>
<L>The bells &s;o merry,</L>
<L>The buzzing cymbal,</L>
<L>And grumbling ba&s;&s;o&mdash;</L>
<L>Oh, wouldn't it vex one to mi&s;s</L>
<L>Such a ravi&s;hing concert as this!</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear Varbel, we have lately pick'd up &s;ome information; &s;earch with me but one day longer,&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Heavens and Earth!&mdash;but where will you &s;earch for her?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here, every where, in every corner of the earth.&mdash;Oh, Lodoi&s;ka! Lodoi&s;ka!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="11" REF="10">
Enter KERA KHAN, and ITHORAK.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>As I hope to be &s;av'd, Sir, there are a couple of Tartars.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>With all my heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>With all your heart! Egad, that's very pretty talking.&mdash;Now, I &s;uppo&s;e, if you don't cut their throats, they'll cut ours.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dare you fight, Varbel?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>I can't tell, I never tried.&mdash;But you're a good ma&s;ter, and I'll &s;tand by you to the la&s;t ga&s;p.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ithorak.</SPEAKER>
<P>From the ca&s;tle, doubtle&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;hall give us information.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Ithorak draws a Pi&s;tol, which Kera Khan &s;trikes out of his hand.</STAGE>
<Q><TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>QUARTETTO.</HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>KERA KHAN&mdash;ITHORAK.</SPEAKER>
<L>Yield your arms on noble quarter;</L>
<L>Yield; re&s;i&s;tance is in vain.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORESKI&mdash;VARBEL.</SPEAKER>
<L>No; fir&s;t win them, haughty Tartar;</L>
<L>Ba&s;e &s;urrender we di&s;dain.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>KERA KHAN&mdash;ITHORAK.</SPEAKER>
<L>Yield, &amp;c.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORESKI&mdash;VARBEL.</SPEAKER>
<L>No, &amp;c.</L>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<STAGE>[They engage. Varbel drives Ithorak before him; Kera Khan is di&s;arm'd; Varbel returns with Ithorak's &s;word.]</STAGE>
<SP>
<PB N="12" REF="11">
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thou art brave, and &s;hould'&s;t be gene|rous; I a&s;k my life; I &s;hould have &s;par'd thine.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't believe him; there are millions of them about: He is only laying a trap to catch you at di&s;advantage.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan</SPEAKER>
<P>Liar!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hold! I tru&s;t to your faith.</P>
<STAGE>[Gives him his &s;word.]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Young man, my obligations to thee &s;hall live in my heart.</P>
<STAGE>[A tumultuous noi&s;e of Tartars is heard.]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>There, there, I told you &s;o; I knew you'd throw us into the hands of the&s;e Tartars again, and I can't go on fighting all night.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan.</SPEAKER>
<P>The&s;e Tartars are at my command.</P>
<STAGE>Enter all the Tartars, headed by ITHORAK, KHOR, JAPHIS, KAJAH, TAMURI, and CAMAZIN.</STAGE>
<P>Halt! halt! re&s;pect the&s;e &s;trangers; they are under my protection.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ithorak.</SPEAKER>
<P>Protection! Kill the &s;laves.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! do you growl cur?</P>
<STAGE>[Throws Ithorak to the ground.]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ithorak.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mercy! mercy!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ari&s;e; and let the mercy I extend teach thee to feel for others.&mdash;Put up. [<HI>the Tartars all &s;hcathe their &s;words.</HI>] You &s;par'd my life, I
<PB N="13" REF="12">have pre&s;erv'd yours. Give me your e&s;teem, and let this embrace confirm us friends.</P>
<STAGE>[Kera Khan and Count, Varbel and Ithorak, embrace.]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>For ever.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Tell me, do you belong to the ca&s;tle? Came you from it when we attack'd you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>No; we are utter &s;trangers here.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan.</SPEAKER>
<P>What is your name?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am the count Flore&s;ki.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan.</SPEAKER>
<P>What is thy name?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>I can't &s;ay, that I have acquir'd any very great name yet, Sir.&mdash;I am the lowly, but faithful, 'Squire of this unhappy young gentleman.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Unhappy, &s;ay'it thou? What can I do for thee?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nothing can relieve my woes, till I find her, for whom alone I live.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan.</SPEAKER>
<P>O, love is thy complaint; that's a pain that never di&s;turbs us Tartars; though we love pretty women heartily too,&mdash;and have plenty of them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>You never &s;aw my Lodoi&s;ka.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Shall we conduct you on your way to her?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alas! I know not where to find her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, wand'ring though the&s;e de|&s;arts after her, without knowing where &s;he is to be found? Are there no other women in the world?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Egad, that's a very &s;en&s;ible que&s;tion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, none for me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="14" REF="13">
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why then we Tartars love wo|men better than you do; for we are fond of all we meet with.&mdash;Can I in any way alleviate thy grief?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Impo&s;&s;ible!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan.</SPEAKER>
<P>We'll talk no more on't then; if I cannot comfort, my curio&s;ity &s;hall not afflict, thee.&mdash; I mu&s;t be gone.&mdash;Once more remember, the&s;e &s;trangers are our friends.</P>
</SP>
<Q><TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD><HI>QUARTETTO</HI> and <HI>CHORUS.</HI></HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>KERA KHAN, ITHORAK, KHOR, JAFHIS.</SPEAKER>
<LG>
<L>We &s;wear, and all our hordes around us,</L>
<L>By the &s;wift arrow and the bow,</L>
<L>Tho' countle&s;s perils &s;hould &s;urround us,</L>
<L>Who injures them becomes our foe.</L>
</LG>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORESKI.</SPEAKER>
<L>Accept our thanks, illu&s;trious chief,</L>
<L>Thy faith and courage well we know,</L>
<L>And, if it could admit relief,</L>
<L>Such friends might &s;oothe Flore&s;ki's woe.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHORUS&mdash;HORDE.</SPEAKER>
<L>We &s;wear, and all our hordes around us,</L>
<L>By the &s;wift arrow and the bow,</L>
<L>Tho' countle&s;s perils &s;hould &s;urround us,</L>
<L>Who injures them becomes our foe.</L>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Before we part, Flore&s;ki, I wou'd yet farther de&s;erve your regard; think not the thir&s;t of plunder drew Kera Khan into the&s;e can|tons;
<PB N="15" REF="14">the baron Lovin&s;ki, who&s;e ca&s;tle you be|hold,&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lovin&s;ki?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan.</SPEAKER>
<P>&mdash;Soon &s;hall he feel my vengeance. I was examining the place; and, to prevent fur|pri&s;e, had charg'd my followers to di&s;arm, and &s;e|cure, all pa&s;&s;engers.&mdash;Knock at his gates; he will not &s;urely refu&s;e a &s;helter to his countrymen; tell him you have been attack'd by the Tartars, by Kera Khan&mdash;he knows my name.&mdash;As I cannot an&s;wer for all our parties that are abroad to night, I advi&s;e you to beg a lodging under his roof; but remember to fly far from it early in the morning; &mdash;early in the morning;&mdash;remember that.&mdash;Give me your hand:&mdash;Adieu, my gallant friend!&mdash; Think &s;ometimes of Kera Khan, and, if ever you want his help, you &s;hall &s;ee how he will &s;erve you. &mdash;March!&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>Exeunt Kera Khan and Tartars.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Egad, the&s;e Tartars are fine fellows!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>And, for that rea&s;on, you were going to chop off the head of their leader.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>The heat of the battle ran away with me; a man has not his courage always at com|mand.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lovin&s;ki!&mdash;I think he's a dependant of Lodoi&s;ka's father.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is he? he'll be no friend of your's then; don't think of lodging here.&mdash;Do, fir, let's take a mouthful, and then pack up and return.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Again return!&mdash;but do you as you will.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="16" REF="15">
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Taking victuals out of the portmanteau)</STAGE>
<P>Come, my dear ma&s;ter;&mdash;look, under their old grated window, there's a &s;nug ho&s;pitable porch for us. (<HI>Sits down in the niche.</HI>) They can't &s;ee us here. (<HI>Eating</HI>) Are you hungry?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, not I.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am very&mdash;that little tilting bout with the Tartar has &s;o &s;harpen'd my &s;tomach, that I cou'd eat&mdash;'gad, I believe I cou'd eat the Tartar him|&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>An adventure of a &s;trange nature!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't let it &s;urpri&s;e you too much; I dare &s;ay, it is not the la&s;t we &s;hall light upon; we are in a fine train for adventures.&mdash;Sir, your good health! [<HI>A large &s;tone falls from the tower.</HI>] Holla! here's an adventure already, of a nature to crack a man's crown.&mdash;Are they throwing the &s;tones of the tower at me?&mdash;I may as well leave table.&mdash;'Much oblig'd to you; but I'm not us'd to de&s;erts at my dinner, and always thought wall-fruit particu|larly unwhole&s;ome.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Silence!&mdash;don't I &s;ee a hand moving there? Stand &s;till, Varbel.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not I, indeed; if you wi&s;h to have an old hou&s;e about yours ears, I don't. [<HI>Another &s;tone falls from the lower, with a paper fa&s;tened to it.</HI>)</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>A &s;econd! what can this mean?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll tell you; it means, that the good people here aren't fond of company who are not invited; and this is civilly to give us notice, that,
<PB N="17" REF="16">if we don't decamp in a moment, we &s;hall have the re&s;t of the ca&s;tle to carry away on our &s;houl|ders.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>(<HI>Taking up the fir&s;t &s;tone.</HI>) What do I &s;ee? writing!&mdash;Varbel&mdash;read, read, what is &s;cratch'd here.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>(<HI>Reading.</HI>) "Oh, Flore&s;ki!&mdash;It is Flore&s;ki." &mdash;Are you &s;ure there are no witches in this wood?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who can know me in this &s;olitude?&mdash; Ha! give me the other.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>(<HI>Giving the 2d. &s;tone.</HI>) Ha! here's a paper.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>(<HI>Snatches the paper, and reads.</HI>) "Inform my father, that Lovin&s;ki has abus'd his confidence, and confines his Lodoi&s;ka in this&mdash;" (<HI>Drops the note.</HI>) Oh, Varbel! &s;he is immur'd in that hor|rible tower.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Poor lady!&mdash;What a damn'd rogue that fellow mu&s;t be!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Lodoi&s;ka! my life! my &s;oul! I will relea&s;e, or die for thee.&mdash;Varbel!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>My lord.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Where is my friend? Where is my Kera Khan?&mdash;call him;&mdash;now, now, I demand his help. &mdash;I rave, I rave&mdash;alas! he's far away.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, &s;o mo&s;t friends are, when you want 'em.</P>
</SP>
<Q><PB N="18" REF="17">
<TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>TRIO.</HEAD>
<STAGE>LODOISKA, COUNT, and VARBEL,</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<L>Flore&s;ki!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<L>'Tis her voice&mdash;O, ble&s;&s;ed day!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Var.</SPEAKER>
<L>Hu&s;h! where we are con&s;ider, pray.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<L>Fly, fly, this in&s;tant, ere my guards appear: No power can &s;ave thee, if they find thee here.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<L>Oh, I've a thou&s;and things to &s;ay!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Var.</SPEAKER>
<L>Another time, &s;ir;&mdash;let's away.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<L>Ah, yet a little moment &s;tay.&mdash; Deare&s;t friend,&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<L>I attend,&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Var.</SPEAKER>
<L>Make an end,&mdash;or I'll begone.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<L>At midnight,&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<L>At midnight,&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varb.</SPEAKER>
<L>At midnight,&mdash;well, well go on.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<L>You may &s;end,&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<L>I may &s;end,&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varb.</SPEAKER>
<L>He may &s;end,&mdash;&s;o, li&s;ten now.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<L>What you write,&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<L>What I write,&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varb.</SPEAKER>
<L>What you write,&mdash;but tell us how.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<L>Tie it to,&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<L>Tie it to,&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varb.</SPEAKER>
<L>Tie it to,&mdash;to what, I pray?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<L>This ribband,&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<L>What ribband?&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varb.</SPEAKER>
<L>A ribband!&mdash;ay, that's the way.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="19" REF="18">
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<L>Given by you,&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<L>Given to you,&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varb.</SPEAKER>
<L>Given by you,&mdash;&s;ee, &s;ee it there.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<L>Which my hand,&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<L>Which thy hand,&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varb.</SPEAKER>
<L>Which her hand,&mdash;'tis good, I &s;wear.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<L>Shall let drop,&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<L>Will let drop,&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varb.</SPEAKER>
<L>Will let drop,&mdash;why &s;ure we dream.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<L>At that hour,&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<L>At that hour,&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varb.</SPEAKER>
<L>At that hour,&mdash;a charming &s;cheme!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<L>From the top,&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<L>From the top,&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varb.</SPEAKER>
<L>From the top,&mdash;now I can tell.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<L>Of the tow'r,&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<L>O, Varbel!&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varb.</SPEAKER>
<L>Yes;&mdash;I &s;ee it very well.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LODOISKA.</SPEAKER>
<L>Ere we part, let me remind you,</L>
<L>Caution now mu&s;t guide your love;</L>
<L>Should the tyrant's ruffians find you,</L>
<L>'Twould your certain ruin prove.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNT.</SPEAKER>
<L>Can I go? and have I found thee,</L>
<L>Added torments but to prove?</L>
<L>Let the tyrant's &s;laves &s;urround me&mdash;</L>
<L>What is death to hopele&s;s love!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="20" REF="19">
<SPEAKER>VARBEL.</SPEAKER>
<L>Come away; let her advi&s;e you,</L>
<L>Hear the voice of anxious love;</L>
<L>If the tyrant's guard e&s;pies you,</L>
<L>'Twill our certain ruin prove.</L>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>She's gone, &s;he's gone!&mdash;Treacherous Lovin&s;ki, dearly &s;halt thou atone this horrid &s;acri|lege!&mdash;Come, let us in&s;tantly confront the mon|&s;ter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mercy on us! Sir, if you appear before him in this emotion, he'll di&s;cover you in a mo|ment, and hang us both up for &s;care-crows on the beams of his draw-bridge.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are in the right&mdash;I have thought better; I'll be calm.&mdash;Lovin&s;ki knows me not.&mdash; Go, take the bugle, and &s;ound boldly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sound the bugle?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sound, I &s;ay!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll do it with all the breath I have in my body.</P>
<STAGE>[Sounds the bugle-horn, a trumpet an&s;wers, and a Page appears upon the ramparts.]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Page.</SPEAKER>
<P>Speak your degree, and what your errand, that a&s;k admittance here?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Gentle our breeding, and to the baron Lovin&s;ki is our greeting. (<HI>Trumpet &s;ounds, and exit Page.</HI>) At length, perhaps, I &s;hall behold her; yet may not this attempt hazard her precious &s;afe|ty? (<HI>The araw-bridge is lower'd</HI>) Hark!&mdash;The &s;e|cret is known only to her father, and this traitor;
<PB N="21" REF="20">&mdash;let me be wary.&mdash;Now ob&s;erve;&mdash;your part is only to confirm my &s;tory.&mdash;Be bold!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Depend on me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>They come.</P>
<STAGE>(Varbel picks up Lodoi&s;ka's note.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE>MARCH. Baron LOVINSKI, ADOLPHUS, GUSTAVUS, MICHAEL, SE|BASTIAN, CASIMIR, STANISLAUS, Two Pages, Guards and Attendants, pa&s;s over the draw-bridge from the ca&s;tle.</STAGE>
<STAGE>The Baron &s;igns to Scha&s;tian and Ca&s;imir, who take their &s;words from the Count and Varbel.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, coward guilt!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>There's an end of our fighting, however.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Approach.&mdash;Who are you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Speak I before the baron Lovin&s;ki?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thou do&s;t.&mdash;What are you?&mdash;and whence came you at this late hour?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>We come from prince Lupau&s;ki; &s;ome Tartars, whom we e&s;cap'd by miracle, plunder'd us of our hor&s;es on the way, and made us much fear we &s;hou'd not have reach'd your ca&s;tle this right.&mdash;Kera Khan&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>That robber, who coops us within our walls!&mdash;But to your bu&s;ine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>We have &s;trict orders from our prince not to communicate, but with your&s;elf in private.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Retire! (<HI>Guards retire.</HI>) Adolphus!&mdash;
<STAGE>(Count &s;eems unwilling to &s;peak before Adolphus.)</STAGE> I conceal nothing from him.&mdash;Now, where are your ma&s;ter's letters to me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="22" REF="21">
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Letters, my Lord?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>He &s;eems confounded.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>You forget; we told you, Sir, the Tar|tars plundered us of our hor&s;es; and, I a&s;&s;ure you, they did not leave our baggage behind them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Know'&s;t thou aught of their contents?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>O, yes, my Lord; the prince, appre|hen&s;ive, perhaps, of our falling among the robbers in the&s;e woods, told us, that they contain'd en|quiries after his daughter Lodoi&s;ka.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lodoi&s;ka!&mdash;Has he then divulg'd the place of her retreat?&mdash;Tell me, where is Lupau&s;ki now?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Being on his progre&s;s to a&s;&s;emble the confederates, I cannot tell preci&s;ely where he is; but, I know, his letters likewi&s;e &s;aid, that you might &s;oon expect him here.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here, &s;ee him here, &s;ay'&s;t thou?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Whi&s;pers Adolphus.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do you ob&s;erve his looks?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, and they frighten me out of my wits.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>It &s;hall be &s;o.&mdash;I am &s;orry to &s;end your ma&s;ter &s;uch unwelcome news; but you will tell him, that Lodoi&s;ka is not here.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not here?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not here.&mdash;Do you mark his emotion?&mdash; To oblige the prince, I undertook, again&s;t my will, to guard her in this ca&s;tle from the Count
<PB N="23" REF="22">Flore&s;ki:&mdash;but it is now four days &s;ince &s;he made her e&s;cape from me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Four days!&mdash;Lying dog!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>She is by this time, I &s;uppo&s;e, in the arms of her beloved Flore&s;ki; if, which I fear was impo&s;&s;ible, &s;he e&s;cap'd the Tartars, that be&s;et the Fore&s;t.&mdash;Go, bear my an&s;wer to your ma&s;ter.&mdash; Begone.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Talks with Adolphus.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, good my Lord, will you di&s;mi&s;s us at this late hour? We are exhau&s;ted with fatigue and hunger; vouch&s;afe us the &s;helter of your roof this night, and to-morrow by day break we will depart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Adolphus.</SPEAKER>
<P>And yet, refu&s;ing to admit his me&s;|&s;engers may rai&s;e &s;u&s;picion in Lupau&s;ki.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>True, true.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Will you my Lord?&mdash;can you bar your gates to us?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, we are likely to have the &s;ky for our te&s;ter to-night.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>It is too late to di&s;mi&s;s you this evening; promi&s;e not to exchange a &s;yllable with any of my people, and you &s;hall &s;tay here to-night; in the morning I will prepare a letter to the prince, which you mu&s;t deliver with the utmo&s;t &s;peed; for it is of moment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>You &s;hall be obey'd.&mdash;We have &s;ucceed|ed; perhaps I may yet re&s;cue her, Varbel; perhaps&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>How now! what's that he &s;ays?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>He &s;ays, that we are lucky fellows to be
<PB N="24" REF="23">re&s;cu'd from the danger of pa&s;&s;ing the night among the wolves and Tartars in the Fore&s;t; and &s;o I think we are.&mdash;We &s;hall be found out, if you don't take better care.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Where &s;hall we lodge the&s;e men?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Adolphus.</SPEAKER>
<P>In the low room by the north po&s;tern.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron</SPEAKER>
<P>It is remote; &s;ee to the bars and bolts.&mdash; Remember your promi&s;e, and keep it faithfully. Follow.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exeunt Baron, and attendants into the ca&s;tle.</STAGE>
<Q><TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>FINALE.</HEAD>
<STAGE>ADOLPHUS, GUSTAVUS, COUNT, VARBEL. <HI>POLISH GUARDS.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ADOLPHUS&mdash;GUSTAVUS.</SPEAKER>
<L>Follow me; but take good care</L>
<L>Not to practi&s;e here deceit;</L>
<L>If you &s;hould, by heav'n, I &s;wear,</L>
<L>In&s;tant death you &s;urely meet.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNT.</SPEAKER>
<L>Let us on; but take good care</L>
<L>Well to colour our deceit;&mdash;</L>
<L>For my love, by heav'n, I &s;wear,</L>
<L>In&s;tant death I'd gladly meet.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VARBEL.</SPEAKER>
<L>Well, go on; and never &s;ear</L>
<L>But I colour the deceit;</L>
<L><PB N="25" REF="24">
For, by heav'n and earth, I &s;wear,</L>
<L>Death I &s;hould be loth to meet.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHORUS of POLISH GUARDS.</SPEAKER>
<L>Follow us; but take good care</L>
<L>Not to practi&s;e here deceit;</L>
<L>If you &s;hould, by heav'n, we &s;wear,</L>
<L>In&s;tant death you &s;urely meet.</L>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<STAGE>Exeunt into the Ca&s;tle.</STAGE>
<TRAILER>END OF THE FIRST ACT.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="act">
<PB N="26" REF="25">
<HEAD>ACT II.</HEAD>
<STAGE>The Act begins on the point of day-break; and the &s;cene repre&s;ents Lodoi&s;ka's Tower, upon a high Terrace, within the ca&s;tle.</STAGE>
<STAGE>OVERTURE.</STAGE>
<STAGE>Enter LODOISKA from the Tower, with the Ribband in her Fland.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodoi&s;ka.</SPEAKER>
<P>The night is almo&s;t pa&s;s'd, and day &s;tands ready to dawn upon the mountains.&mdash;Oh, Flore&s;ki, in vain I have watch'd for thy expected letter!&mdash;My heart &s;inks in me with the &s;ear of having betray'd thee into the hands of Lovin&s;ki. I knew thy faithful love, I knew thy impetuous valour.&mdash;Why did I reveal my&s;elf?&mdash;Yet will I hope,&mdash;Kind hope, thou only friend that vi&s;ite&s;t the unhappy, dwell with me &s;till, and calm the crowd|ing terrors that oppre&s;s me!</P>
<Q><PB N="27" REF="26">
<TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>AIR.</HEAD>
<LG N="1">
<HEAD>I.</HEAD>
<L>Ye &s;treams, that round my pri&s;on creep,</L>
<L>If on your mo&s;&s;y banks you &s;ee</L>
<L>My gallant lover &s;tand and weep,</L>
<L>Oh, murmur this command from me;&mdash;</L>
<L>Thy mi&s;tre&s;s bids thee ha&s;te away,</L>
<L>And &s;hun the broad-ey'd, watchful, day.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2">
<HEAD>II.</HEAD>
<L>Ye gales, that love with me to &s;igh,</L>
<L>If in your breezy &s;light you &s;ee</L>
<L>My dear Flore&s;ki ling'ring nigh,</L>
<L>Oh, whi&s;per this command from me;&mdash;</L>
<L>Thy mi&s;tre&s;s bids thee ha&s;te away,</L>
<L>And &s;hun the broad-ey'd, watchful, day.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<P>Hark! yes I hear a noi&s;e&mdash;Let me retire to my &s;ad pri&s;on, till I again can breathe the fre&s;hne&s;s of the air in &s;olitude; for every object here is odious to me.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit into the Tower, leaving the Ribband on the rails of the ttrraee.</STAGE>
<STAGE>Enter COUNT FLORESKI from an inner Court.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, no where, to be found through all courts!&mdash;My love, my life, and mu&s;t I lo&s;e thee? Day breaks apace.&mdash;I mu&s;t go back, or be di&s;cover'd.&mdash;Ha! another querter!&mdash; I will explore thee, be the con&s;equences what they may.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit through a vaulted pa&s;&s;age.</STAGE>
<STAGE><PB N="28" REF="27">
Enter VARBEL, from a di&s;tant Ca&s;emate.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir! Sir!&mdash;hi&s;t, hi&s;t.&mdash;Have you found her? Why don't you &s;peak to one now?&mdash;He's not here.&mdash;I thought I heard him this moment too. So, I have lo&s;t my ma&s;ter in the dark, and now, if any of the gentlemen of this humane family happen to &s;tumble upon me, my poor dear life's not worth a minute's purcha&s;e.&mdash;He's poring about after his Lodoi&s;ka; the deu&s;e a bit does he think of me.&mdash;Though our window was double and treble barr'd, and barricado'd, he bur&s;t away the bolts with a &s;nap of his finger; and, I believe, like Mr. What d'ye call him, he'd have bur&s;t the gates of Hell to come at his mi&s;tre&s;s.&mdash;I can't con|ceive what's the matter with me to night; I &s;ee Spectres and Phantoms before me at every turn.&mdash; If a man cou'd admini&s;ter courage to him&s;elf when he wanted it, I'd take a good do&s;e of it now; and yet, I dare &s;ay, &s;ome people wou'd be much more fright|en'd than I am.&mdash;Mercy on us! what's that?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Re-enter the COUNT.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>My &s;earch is all in vain.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! is it nothing but you, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Varbel? Why did not you wait in the room, as I order'd you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>I don't know how it is; but, to tell you the truth, Sir, I'm lately grown a little afraid of keeping my own company.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>His fears will ruin me at la&s;t.&mdash;Afraid?&mdash; You, who fought &s;o bravely again&s;t the Tartars?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="29" REF="28">
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>I tell you what; I'll fight the Devil him&s;elf by day light; but a gho&s;t in the dark is quite another thing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mu&s;t all my hazards then prove fruitle&s;s?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, we have pa&s;s'd the night here to very little purpo&s;e; and without any &s;upper too;&mdash; they forgot that part of the ceremony;&mdash;And, now I think on't, I believe, that's what makes me &s;o nervous.&mdash;Hunger will tame the courage of a lion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>To know that &s;he is here, and not to &s;ee her!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do, let's go back, and try if we can hinder their &s;eeing, that we have broke out of the dog-hole they lock'd us in.&mdash;Con&s;ider, he'll be coming to you with his letter pre&s;ently.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Am I deceiv'd? That ribband!&mdash;This, this is, perhaps, the very tower.&mdash;Now be propi|tious, Heav'n!&mdash;My love! my Lodoi&s;ka!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>A drum beats the reveille.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here they are, as I hope to be &s;av'd.&mdash; It's all over with us.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, no; run back to our room a mo|ment.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter SEBASTIAN, STANISLAUS, MICHAEL and CASIMIR, at the Head of the Baron's Guards.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>They're coming at that &s;ide.&mdash;Oh! a plague o' this caterwauling!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here, here; till they are gone.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Gu&s;tavus pa&s;&s;es along the Terrace into Lodoiska's Tower.]</STAGE>
<STAGE>[The Count and Varbelretire into a Rece&s;s under the Terrace.]</STAGE>
<STAGE><PB N="30" REF="29">
Enter the BARON, and ADOLPHUS, with a Letter.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>(<HI>To Seba&s;tian and guards</HI>) Stay there; and, on your lives, be &s;ilent.&mdash;Is the letter to Lupau&s;ki ready?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Adol.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have it.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Gives the letter to the Baron, who reads it.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>The Baron him&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now we are in a hopeful condition!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is Gu&s;tavus gone upon my &s;tratagem to per&s;uade the Prince&s;s of Flore&s;ki's death?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Adol.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;aw him enter the Tower this moment.&mdash; And now, let me again entreat you to retire to re&s;t; they have ju&s;t beat the Reveille; 'tis high morning; and for the&s;e two nights you have not ta&s;ted &s;leep.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>I tell thee, my anxiety, my doubts, my fears, have drawn me hither; nor will I &s;tir, 'till the re&s;ult of this la&s;t effort pronounce me ble&s;t, or cur&s;t for ever.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Adol.</SPEAKER>
<P>But, Sir,&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! my Friend, you know my fatal pa&s;&s;ion&mdash;The &s;corn &s;he treats me with, my bar|barity to her, my ingratitude to her father, my hope, and my de&s;pair, drive me to madne&s;s.&mdash; There is no re&s;t for me.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Adol.</SPEAKER>
<P>But good my Lord, in&s;tead of treating her with &s;o much rigour, why not demand her frankly of her father? His high regard for you,&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is nothing but the in&s;olence of obligation; name it not.&mdash;His family has given &s;overeigns to
<PB N="31" REF="30">Poland; he would reject with &s;corn the offers of an humble Baron.&mdash;You know the pride, the unrelenting ob&s;tinacy, of this old man;&mdash;he wou'd indignantly withdraw her from my ca&s;tle, and I&mdash; in&s;upportable!&mdash;&s;hou'd never, never &s;ee her more!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Adol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yet &s;oon you mu&s;t expect him to recall her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Recall her!&mdash;No.&mdash;I have &s;et loo&s;e my love and my ambition; they have hurried me be|yond the power of retreat, and now &s;he &s;hall be mine, if force, or fraud, or any means can win her. &mdash;Soft,&mdash;&s;he appears.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then &s;he is here!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hu&s;h!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter LODOISKA from the Tower, following GUSTAVUS, who, repa&s;&s;ing the Terrace, is met by the BARON and ADOLPHUS, anxious to hear how the Prince&s;s had received his Me&s;&s;age.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dead! Kill'd by the Tartars!&mdash;No, no, Lovin&s;ki is the a&s;&s;a&s;&s;in&mdash;Oh! my love, 'twas I, 'twas I betray'd thee into his power.</P>
<Q><TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>ROMANCE.</HEAD>
<L>Adieu, my Flore&s;ki, for ever,</L>
<L>And welcome the follows I prove!&mdash;</L>
<L>Why, &s;ate, &s;till delight'&s;t thou to &s;ever</L>
<L>The bo&s;oms united by love?&mdash;</L>
<L>Clos'd is that eye,</L>
<L>Mute is the tongue,</L>
<L><PB N="32" REF="31">
On which my &s;oul</L>
<L>Enraptur'd hung!&mdash;</L>
<L>He's gone, he's dead,&mdash;and I remain</L>
<L>To &s;igh, and weep,&mdash;alas! in vain.</L>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>She thinks me murder'd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;o we &s;hall be in a minute, if you don't hold your tongue.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Symphony.&mdash;The Baron, Gu&s;tavus &amp; Adolphus, advance.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thou ha&s;t di&s;charg'd it well.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yet this may be &s;ome new device of Lovin&s;ki's.</P>
<Q><TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>ROMANCE.</HEAD>
<L>Clos'd is that eye,</L>
<L>Mute is the tongue,</L>
<L>On which my &s;oul</L>
<L>Enraptur'd hung!&mdash;</L>
<L>He's gone, he's dead, and I remain</L>
<L>To &s;igh, and weep, alas! in vain.</L>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
</SP>
<Q><TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>ROMANCE&mdash;QUINTETTO.</HEAD>
<STAGE>LODOISKA, COUNT, VARBEL, ADOLPHUS, GUSTAVUS.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LODOISKA.</SPEAKER>
<L>If I may tru&s;t</L>
<L>This faithful heart,</L>
<L>We &s;oon &s;hall meet</L>
<L>No more to part;</L>
<L><PB N="33" REF="32">
He's gone, nor &s;hall I long remain,</L>
<L>To &s;igh, and weep,&mdash;alas! in vain.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNT.</SPEAKER>
<L>If I may tru&s;t</L>
<L>This faithful heart,</L>
<L>We &s;oon &s;hall meet</L>
<L>No more to part;</L>
<L>Oh, mu&s;t I then conceal'd remain,</L>
<L>And know thou weep'&s;t my lo&s;s in vain!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VARBEL.</SPEAKER>
<L>If I may tru&s;t</L>
<L>My boding heart,</L>
<L>Too &s;oon your '&s;quire</L>
<L>And you will part;</L>
<L>Your mi&s;tre&s;s then mu&s;t here remain,</L>
<L>To &s;igh, and weep our lo&s;s in vain.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ADOLPHUS&mdash;GUSTAVUS.</SPEAKER>
<L>Would he but tru&s;t</L>
<L>My duteous heart,</L>
<L>en &s;hould he know</L>
<L>The hone&s;t part</L>
<L><PB N="34" REF="33">
I'd take his mi&s;tre&s;s to obtain,</L>
<L>Nor let him &s;igh, and love, in vain.</L>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<STAGE>The Baron, hearing voices in the rece&s;s, &s;ends Seba&s;|tian to take Lodoiska away, then leads his guard round through the vanited pa&s;&s;age, and, while Seba&s;tian hur|ries the prince&s;s into the tower, &s;urprizes the Count and Varbel.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>One word, and you are dead.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Villains! Cowards!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>One word, and we are dead.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>The me&s;lengers!&mdash;Then 'tis impo&s;&s;ible to blind Lupau&s;ki. How have you dar'd, vile &s;pies, to built the doors that held you?&mdash;Who told you the prince&s;s was in that tower?&mdash;But you &s;hall <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 span"> her face.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>There, I thought it would come to this <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 span">.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Before her face!&mdash;Then I am ble&s;t in|deed; I &s;hall once more behold her.&mdash;Come, why deed thou pau&s;e?&mdash;Summon thy executioners, pre|pue the rack, and thou &s;halt &s;ee me &s;pring to my glorious death, proud as impatient martyrs on their road to heaven.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, you forget me; I've travell'd with you very contentedly &s;o far; but I'm not prepared to take the journey you talk of at pre&s;ent.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(To Gu&s;tavus and Adolphus.)</STAGE>
<P>Such fortitude &s;uits ill with his condition; &s;omething whi&s;pers me they are not what they &s;ay;&mdash;I'll prove them to
<PB N="35" REF="34">the quick.&mdash;One way you yet may &s;ave your&s;elves, and Lodoi&s;ka.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray, &s;ir, what's that?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Say, truly, whence did you learn that &s;he was &s;till in my ca&s;tle? Speak, I &s;ay, or Lodoi&s;ka's life&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Offering him her note.)</STAGE>
<P>Give him her let|ter; give him her letter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Snatching it.)</STAGE>
<P>Slave!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>It's the way to &s;ave us all.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are right.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Seek not to deceive, but an&s;wer in&s;tant|ly, or&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>I learnt it from her&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Her&s;elf!&mdash;Have you then &s;een her?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, no, upon my honour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Giving the note.)</STAGE>
<P>She dropt it from her tower la&s;t night.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Reads.)</STAGE>
<P>"Let my father know that Lo|vin&s;ki has abus'd his con&s;idence, and con&s;ines his Lodoi&s;ka in this tower, till &s;he con&s;ent to give him her hand.&mdash;My guard will return in a moment,&mdash;fly."&mdash;Cur&s;e on my imprudence!&mdash;But they have not yet &s;een her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>You find, my lord, we &s;corn to deceive you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis well you do;&mdash;your companion's &s;udden warmth gave me ill thoughts of you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah! poor fellow! He can't help it; &s;he was a very kind lady to him.&mdash;I am always telling
<PB N="36" REF="35">you of your flying into &s;uch pa&s;&s;ions, you fooli&s;h&mdash; <STAGE>(<HI>Strikes him.</HI>)</STAGE> I beg your pardon, fir; kick me whenever you like.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ee, notwith&s;tanding his firmne&s;s, they are but &s;ervants, inflam'd by zeal and affection for their mi&s;tre&s;s;&mdash;they &s;hall &s;erve my de&s;ign.&mdash;I have promis'd you life,&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, &s;ir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>I add one only condition; &s;ee you di&s;|charge it to the point; your fate and mine depends on it.&mdash;I have a&s;&s;ur'd the prince&s;s that Flore&s;ki is dead; my intelligence appears to be &s;u&s;pected; but &s;he can doubt no longer, if once &s;he hears it confirm'd by you in per&s;on:&mdash;This you mu&s;t in|&s;tantly perform in my pre&s;ence, or by my&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't look &s;o frightful, &s;ir, and we'll do whatever you plea&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, I obey.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Enough.&mdash;Bring Lodoi&s;ka hither.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(<HI>Exit Seba&s;ian into the tower.</HI>)</STAGE>
<SP>
<P><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">erving me, you &s;ave your&s;elves;&mdash;retire; I &s;hall call for you at your time to appear before her.&mdash;Gu&s;tavus, in&s;truct them in your le&s;&s;on.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Exeunt Cu&s;tavus, the Count, and Varbel).</STAGE>
<STAGE>Enter LODOISKA and SEEASTIAN from the Tower.</STAGE>
<SP>
<P>I triumph.&mdash;The prince&s;s (women &s;ometimes for|get the a&s;hes of a buried lover) when once con|vine'd my hated rival is no more, may be per&s;uad|ed&mdash;Oh, tran&s;porting thought!&mdash;The obedient
<PB N="37" REF="36">prie&s;t is ready.&mdash;Once mine, let prince Lupau|&s;ki come; let him be told how I have won his daughter, and all his wide po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ions; let him re&s;ent, &s;he will forgive, and plead for me. How beautiful &s;he is!&mdash;What &s;till in tears? 'Tis in your power, madam, to bid your own afflictions cea&s;e, only by pitying mine.&mdash;Ah! why that &s;corn|ful frown?&mdash;What, will you never, never break this cruel and di&s;dainful &s;ilence?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is my fate too re&s;olv'd upon?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>On thee depends my every hope of hap|pine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Happine&s;s!&mdash;To what happine&s;s can that unfeeling heart pretend? By what authority do you confine me here? My fond father committed me to your duty, not to your cu&s;tody; he delivered me to a friend, not to a goaler.&mdash;You have taken from me the poor women that &s;erv'd me; if I con|ver&s;e, you mu&s;t be my companion; and if I wi&s;h to live,&mdash;as &s;till I do, for thee, Flore&s;ki!&mdash;'tis from that barb'rous hand I mu&s;t accept my &s;u&s;tenance.&mdash;Have you a parent's power with me?&mdash;or a hu&s;band's right?&mdash;That you &s;hall never have;&mdash;no,&mdash;never&mdash;and 'tis only once more to a&s;&s;ure you of my fix'd abhorrence, that I now break my di&s;|dainful &s;ilence for the la&s;t time.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis plain, &s;he di&s;believes&mdash;The doubts you have of count Flore&s;ki's death, madam, cau&s;e this in&s;en&s;ibility to all I &s;uffer; 'tis time they were at once remov'd.&mdash;Know then, two of your father's
<PB N="38" REF="37">&s;ervants, who la&s;t night pa&s;s'd the fore&s;t, are at hand to&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Exit Adolphus.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<P>La&s;t night! The fore&s;t!&mdash;It is true then. Oh, my Flore&s;ki!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Advance.&mdash;No, be a&s;&s;ur'd, proud fair one, tho&s;e eyes &s;hall never &s;ee Flore&s;ki more.&mdash;Ad|vance, I &s;ay.&mdash;Behold.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter the Count, VARBEL, GUSTAVUS, and ADOLPHUS.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hold, heart, a little while!&mdash;Flore&s;ki!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is no more, madam;&mdash;We la&s;t night found him in the wood, kill'd by the Tartars, as we gue&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall di&s;cover all.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam, you know the&s;e men.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I do; I do; and every doubt of my Flo|re&s;ki's death at la&s;t is ended.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>She bears the &s;hock more firmly than I expected.&mdash;If my&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Spare me, my lord&mdash;The &s;urprize, the emotion, the &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Flore&s;ki, madam, &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pronounce his hated name no more.&mdash;Oh Lodoi&s;ka, when I reflect on what my jealous apprehen&s;ions have made you &s;uffer, have I not cau&s;e to hate him? Pardon, pardon tho&s;e &s;everi|ties my heart always di&s;avow'd, and which, be|lieve me, have been inflicted more upon my&s;elf, than you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="39" REF="38">
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Vain man!&mdash;Think you your meaning hid to me?&mdash;Come, dare for once to &s;peak a truth; it is not love, 'tis your ambition &s;eeks the heire&s;s of the prince Lupau&s;ki.&mdash;For &s;hame! For &s;hame!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>In&s;ulted!&mdash;I'll bear no more.&mdash;Hence, idle &s;cruples!&mdash;Go, call the prie&s;t&mdash;Ha&s;te, fly.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Exit Adolphus.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<P>This moment makes you mine.&mdash;And you, tell her this in&s;tant 'tis her father's will; or I revoke the promis'd life I gave you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Tell her, tell her any thing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, my father, where are you now?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>I will protect, or die for you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Relent, proud fair;&mdash;the prie&s;t is here&mdash;Hark! hark!&mdash;he comes, he comes.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter ADOLPHUS.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Adol.</SPEAKER>
<P>My lord, the prince Lupausei is arriv'd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Arriv'd?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Good heaven!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am di&s;cover'd then, and all is lo&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here's another adventure!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Speak, tell me,&mdash;has he a numerous train?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Adol.</SPEAKER>
<P>But two attendants.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then let him come!&mdash;I live again.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Prince Lupau&s;ki.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Without)</STAGE>
<P>Where, where is &s;he?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter Prince LUPAUSKI.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, &s;ir!
<STAGE>(<HI>Knceling</HI>)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="40" REF="39">
<SPEAKER>Prince.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Rai&s;ing &amp; embracing her)</STAGE>
<P>My child! My Lodoi&s;ka!&mdash;Ble&s;&s;ings, ble&s;&s;ings on thee!&mdash;My friend, I cou'd not hope at parting to meet you again &s;o &s;oon; but the confederates are already&mdash;What do I &s;ee?&mdash;Am I deceiv'd?&mdash;The count Flore&s;ki here?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>There,&mdash;now the murder's out.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Flore&s;ki!&mdash;This &s;lave, is he the count Flore&s;ki?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes,&mdash;him&s;elf.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Prince.</SPEAKER>
<P>How has he gain'd admittance to&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>By a cowardly, mean artifice;&mdash;he pre|tended him&s;elf one of your &s;ervants, &s;ent with&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>What cou'd I do, di&s;arm'd, again&s;t thee and thy banditti?&mdash;The artifice thou would'&s;t re|proach me with was bold and honourable; to op|po&s;e &s;tratagem to per&s;idy, and cruelty, like thine, is acting according to the laws of ju&s;tice, and vin|dicating tho&s;e of humanity.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Prince.</SPEAKER>
<P>What's that he &s;ays? To per&s;idy and cruelty like thine? My friend,&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now comes his turn, I hope.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! my father, you would not think what I have &s;uffer'd &s;ince you &s;aw me.&mdash;That friend has forc'd my faithful &s;ervants from about me; that friend has in&s;ulted my unprotected &s;itua|tion with his dete&s;ted offers;&mdash;that friend has bar|barou&s;ly impri&s;on'd me,&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Prince.</SPEAKER>
<P>My daughter!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<P>To extort from me my con&s;ent to a
<PB N="41" REF="40">union, I wou'd gladly die ten thou&s;and deaths to avoid.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Prince.</SPEAKER>
<P>Cou'd you thus violate the laws of ho&s;|pitality? Cou'd you &s;o far forget the bounties I have &s;hower'd upon you?&mdash;My heart repos'd it|&s;elf on yours; &s;eeking a tender refuge for my child, I gave her to your care, as into a holy &s;anc|tuary; you receiv'd from me the &s;tronge&s;t proof of love a friend cou'd give; be a father for one in&s;tant, and judge whether I cou'd have con&s;ided to you a tru&s;t more dear, more &s;acred.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Upon my &s;oul, he's a fine &s;pokon old gentleman.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mu&s;t I then lo&s;e her?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Gives directions to his officers.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Prince.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, thou!&mdash;My va&s;&s;al!&mdash;thou!&mdash;Let's begone.&mdash;I'll take &s;uch vengeance on his treachery, that&mdash;Follow me, my daughter; let's quit for ever this man&s;ion of ingratitude.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>The &s;ooner the better. What a lucky e&s;cape!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Guards.&mdash;Not &s;o fa&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Officers &s;eize the Prince, Lodoiska, Floreski &amp; Varbel.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>What the devil's the matter now?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>This ca&s;tle is your pri&s;on;&mdash;away, con|fine them, as I order'd you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Gentlemen! friends! only hear me!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Two guards bear off Varbel.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Prince.</SPEAKER>
<P>What do'&s;t thou mean?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Never to part with her.&mdash;Away, away.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="42" REF="41">
<SPEAKER>Prince.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, my poor daughter!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(<HI>Exit guarded.</HI>)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<P>My father!&mdash;My Flore&s;ki!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(<HI>The Baron bears off Lodoiska.</HI>)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>My love! My love!</P>
<Q><TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>AIR.</HEAD>
<LG>
<L>De&s;cend, &s;ome warring angel,</L>
<L>In lightning to my aid,</L>
<L>To bla&s;t the &s;avage tyrant,</L>
<L>And right an injur'd maid!</L>
<L>Subdued by fate, to you I kneel;</L>
<L>You look like men, like men &s;hould feel.&mdash;</L>
<L>Fool! not to know,</L>
<L>They laugh at woe.&mdash;</L>
<L>De&s;cend, &s;ome warring angel,</L>
<L>In lightning to my aid,</L>
<L>To bla&s;t the &s;avage tyrant,</L>
<L>And right an injur'd maid!</L>
<L>Let my Lodoi&s;ka's charms</L>
<L>In your hearts compa&s;&s;ion move;</L>
<L>Soldiers, con&s;ecrate your arms</L>
<L>At the &s;hrine of faithful love.</L>
<L>De&s;cend, &s;ome warring angel,</L>
<L>In lightning to my aid,</L>
<L>To bla&s;t the &s;avage tyrant,</L>
<L>And right an injur'd maid!</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
</SP>
<STAGE>(<HI>Exit guarded.</HI>)</STAGE>
<TRAILER>END OF THE SECOND ACT.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="3" TYPE="act">
<PB N="43" REF="42">
<HEAD>ACT III.</HEAD>
<STAGE>OVERTURE.</STAGE>
<STAGE>The act begins early in the morning; and the &s;cene repre&s;ents a hall and gallery in the ca&s;tle.</STAGE>
<STAGE>Enter Two Pages, Baron LOVINSKI, ADOLPHUS, GUSTA|VUS, CASIMIR, SEBASTIAN, STANISLAUS, and MICHAEL, from a &s;ubterraneous pa&s;&s;age.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis all in vain; I cannot &s;hake 'em.&mdash;Cur&s;e on their ob&s;tinacy!&mdash;Love &s;ires Flore&s;ki's brea&s;t, and rage the father's; carele&s;s alike of menaces and &s;oothing, each braves me to my wor&s;t.&mdash;Death and perdition! Let the wor&s;t fall on 'em. Is all prepared for in&s;tant execution?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Adol.</SPEAKER>
<P>It is, my lord.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Still would I have thee mine, O Lodo|i&s;ka! con&s;enting, uncon&s;train'd;&mdash;but, whil&s;t my rival lives, that hope's impo&s;&s;ible.&mdash;Ha! tell me, where is the forward fool, that waited on Flore&s;ki?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Adol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Confin'd, as you commanded.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha&s;te, bring him to me.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Exeunt Adol|phus and Gu&s;tavus through the gallery.</HI>)</STAGE>
<P>I may, per|haps,
<PB N="44" REF="43">per&s;uade this wretch to think his own life more precious than his lord's.&mdash;If I fail here,&mdash;I &s;hudder at the thought of my own purpo&s;es.&mdash;Love, hatred, jealou&s;y, ambition, &s;corn and fury rack my di&s;tracted brain, and rend my heart in pieces.&mdash;Would I were dead my&s;elf!</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Throws him|&s;elf into a chair.</HI>)</STAGE>
<P>Pr'ythee, good boy, &s;ing me tha<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> gentle &s;train, yon lady lov'd; your pretty melody may calm the ragings of the fiend within me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>I&s;t. Page.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'm &s;orry, &s;ir, to &s;ee you &s;o unhappy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron,</SPEAKER>
<P>Sing, &s;ing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FIRST PAGE.</SPEAKER>
<Q><TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>AIR.</HEAD>
<LG N="1">
<HEAD>I.</HEAD>
<L>SWEET bird, that cheer'st the heavy hours</L>
<L>Of winter's dreary reign,</L>
<L>O, &s;till exert thy tuneful pow'rs,</L>
<L>And pour the vocal &s;train!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2">
<HEAD>II.</HEAD>
<L>Go not to &s;eek a &s;canty fare</L>
<L>From nature's frozen hand,</L>
<L>Whil&s;t I, with gratitude, prepare</L>
<L>The food thy wants demand.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3">
<HEAD>III.</HEAD>
<L>Dome&s;tic bird, with me remain,</L>
<L>Until next verdant &s;pring</L>
<L>Again &s;hall bring the woodland train,</L>
<L>Their grateful tribute bring.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4">
<PB N="45" REF="44">
<HEAD>IV.</HEAD>
<L>Sweet Robin, then thou may'&s;t explore</L>
<L>And join the feather'd throng,</L>
<L>And ev'ry vocal bu&s;h &s;hall pour</L>
<L>The energy of &s;ong.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well &s;ung, my boy; I thank your pains, though fruitle&s;s.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter ADOLPHUS, VARBEL, &amp; GUSTAVUS, from the gallery.</STAGE>
<P>He's coming.&mdash;Leave me awhile.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Exeunt Pages, Seba&s;tian, Ca&s;imir, Stani&s;laus, and Michael.</HI>)</STAGE>
<P>Threats will do much, gold more, with ba&s;e-born poverty; both &s;hall be tried.</P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, this is &s;omething like now;&mdash;now I'll talk to you;&mdash;this it is to fall among&s;t men, as it were, &s;omething like men.&mdash;Gentlemen, you have bound me for ever by letting me loo&s;e, and my legs ache to prove their &s;en&s;e of your kindne&s;s by &s;craping their leave, and giving you no farther trouble about 'em.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Seeing the Baron.</HI>)</STAGE>
<P>The man|tiger to &s;wallow me up for his breakfa&s;t.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>You &s;erve Flore&s;ki.&mdash;Why do you trem|ble?&mdash;You have nothing to fear.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, I know, &s;ir;&mdash;but I've had a damp lodging, and I think it's rather chilly this morn|ing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>In one word, your ma&s;ter is to die,&mdash;now, in&s;tantly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'm very &s;orry for it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="46" REF="45">
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have ob&s;erv'd your fidelity, your affec|tion to him.&mdash;I'll take you into my &s;ervice; I love your virtue, and would reward it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'm afraid I &s;hould make but a bad &s;er|vant to you; you had better turn me out o'doors at once, I think&mdash;I had rather&mdash;Do, &s;ir;&mdash;and let my virtue be its own reward.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>No fooling.&mdash;Your romantick lord &s;eems ambitious of dying in this cau&s;e, that he may live lamented in the hi&s;tory of faithful and unfortunate lovers; you, perhaps, a&s;pire to imitate him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>I can't &s;ay, that I do.&mdash;Ambition's a great thing with great folks, I believe; but, for my own poor part, I &s;olemnly a&s;&s;ure you, I had rather live three days in this world, bad as it is, than a thou&s;and years in the be&s;t hi&s;tory that will ever be written.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>I take you at your word;&mdash;there's a poor earne&s;t of my future bounty.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>A pur&s;e!&mdash;What's this for?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Follow, and, as we go, I will in&s;truct you in a &s;hort tale, that at once rids me of Flore&s;ki, and gives you life and fortune.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>My lord, I'm in peril, and poor;&mdash;and I value life and fortune as much as another man; but, I hope, I &s;hall never think 'em worth buying at the price of fal&s;e witne&s;s again&s;t my ma&s;ter.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Throws down the Pur&s;e.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<PB N="47" REF="46">
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha!&mdash;do you trifle, &s;lave? Nay, then I mu&s;t&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Gives orders to Adolphus.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>What's he going to do now?&mdash;I wi&s;h I was fighting the Tartars again, with all my heart!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Him, her, the prince,&mdash;all, all,&mdash;here, now, before my eyes.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Exit Adolphus.</HI>)</STAGE>
<P>The father and the daughter &s;hall behold him, as the blow falls, and from his doom be taught to dread their own.&mdash;For thee, vile reptile,&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Flouri&s;h of drums and trumpets, with cla&s;hing of &s;words, and &s;houts of "Victory, victory! Kera Khan.")</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>They're come, they're come&mdash;Here is an adventure!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter SEBASTIAN, MRCHAEL, CASIMIR, STANISLAUS, ADOLPHUS, Soldiers and Standard-Bearer.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron,</SPEAKER>
<P>The matter?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ca&s;imir.</SPEAKER>
<P>The Tartars are within the walls; the Ea&s;tern towers are blazing; flame and the &s;word rage round; the &s;oldiers fly; ha&s;te, or we peri&s;h all.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sound, &s;ound to arms.&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Exeunt Stani|&s;laus and two &s;oldiers.</HI>)</STAGE>
<P>Rally 'em in the North court, and man the ramparts; there we'll &s;tand it out;&mdash;fly, ha&s;te, I follow.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Exeunt Adolphus and four &s;oldiers.</HI>)</STAGE>
<P>Bring me my arms.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Exeunt Michael, Gu&s;tavus, and Ca&s;imir.</HI>)</STAGE>
<P>Bear off that &s;lave, till I have time to torture him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="48" REF="47">
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>A re&s;pite, a re&s;pite!&mdash;I &s;hall love a Tartar as long as I live.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Exeunt Varbel, Seba&s;tian, and two &s;oldiers.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Baron.</SPEAKER>
<P>Away, away with him!&mdash;Whither am I going?</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Enter Gu&s;tavus, Michael, and Ca&s;imir, with the Baron's helmet, &s;hield, and battle-axe.</HI>)</STAGE>
<P>What's Lodoiska now? Lo&s;t, lo&s;t to me for ever! The hel<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">e&s;s prize of &s;ome fierce lawle&s;s &s;avage.&mdash;Horrible thought!</P>
<STAGE>(Martial Symphony&mdash;The Baron &s;eizes his helmet.)</STAGE>
<P>Where is her father?&mdash;My friend, my benefactor?&mdash;All bleeding, mangled, murder'd.&mdash;Frightful image!&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(Martial Symphony&mdash;The Baron braces on his &s;hield.)</STAGE>
<P>Hark! my &s;oul's beat down, down to the very ground.</P>
<STAGE>(Martial Symphony&mdash;The Baron &s;natches his battle-axe.)</STAGE>
<P>The tempe&s;t &s;wells&mdash;Floreski too, perhaps, directs the &s;torm, thundering and fierce in arms. That burning thought has rouzed me.&mdash;Out, out, and on 'em.&mdash;No word, but fight, till death, or con|que&s;t, end our plagues for ever.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Exeunt Baron, Officers, and Guards.)</STAGE>
<STAGE>The doors of the Hall are bur&s;t open, when <HI>Ithorak, Khor, Japhis, Camazin, Kajah, Tamuri,</HI> and a crowd of Tartars ru&s;h in, &s;ome louded with booty, and others bear|ing off the women they have met with in the ca&s;tle.</STAGE>
<Q><PB N="49" REF="48">
<TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>CHORUS. OF TARTARS and CAPTIVES.</HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAPTIVES.</SPEAKER>
<L>Have pity on us, pray!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>TARTARS.</SPEAKER>
<L>Come, &s;weet la&s;&s;es, come away;</L>
<L>With us the live-long day</L>
<L>You'll wa&s;te in am'rous play.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAPTIVES.</SPEAKER>
<L>No; we'll peri&s;h faithful martyrs</L>
<L>To our hu&s;bands, and our &s;ires.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>TARTARS.</SPEAKER>
<L>Ha!&mdash;no, no; we gallant Tartars</L>
<L>Are only cruel then,</L>
<L>When we contend with men;</L>
<L>But lovely woman kindles gentler &s;ires.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAPTIVES.</SPEAKER>
<L>Ah, yet re&s;tore us to our kindred dear!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>TARTARS.</SPEAKER>
<L>P&s;ha! you nothing have to <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ear;&mdash;</L>
<L>You mu&s;t away,</L>
<L>No more delay.</L>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<STAGE>(The women are borne off, other Tartars remain.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<PB N="50" REF="49">
<SPEAKER>Kajah.</SPEAKER>
<P>At la&s;t we are ma&s;ters of the ca&s;tle.&mdash;It has co&s;t us &s;ome trouble too; the fellows fought like mad-men.&mdash;Have you di&s;arm'd, and clapt them into the dungeons, where we found &s;o many of our countrymen?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Japhis.</SPEAKER>
<P>Our comrades are at it now, break|ing open and locking up.&mdash;But can any body tell why Kera Khan &s;o &s;trictly charg'd us to take Lovin&s;ki alive?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Khor.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hope the other party have him fa&s;t by this time&mdash;Do you think he'll ever forget the death of his father?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>All.</SPEAKER>
<P>Never, never.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ithorak.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, my boys, now away to our plun|der, and divide faithfully.&mdash;You know what &s;hare mu&s;t be re&s;erv'd for Kera Khan.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kajah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, yes, we know the booty he loves be&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Japhis.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, ay, give him the women, he'll give us the gold.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elor.</SPEAKER>
<P>And the wine too.</P>
</SP>
<Q><TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>SONG and CHORUS.</HEAD>
<STAGE>KHOR, JAPHIS, ITHORAK and HORDE.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>KHOR.</SPEAKER>
<L>When the darken'd midnight &s;ky</L>
<L>Howls with wild tempertuous cry,</L>
<L>Then requit the Tartar plain,</L>
<L>Death and terror in our train&mdash;</L>
<L><PB N="51" REF="50">
Where the &s;weeping vengeance drives,</L>
<L>Hopele&s;s man in horror flies;</L>
<L>Worlds of wealth, and worlds of wives,</L>
<L>Are the hardy TARTARS' PRIZE.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHORUS&mdash;HORDE.</SPEAKER>
<L>Worlds of wealth, and worlds of wives,</L>
<L>Are the hardy TARTARS' PRIZE.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JAPHIS.</SPEAKER>
<L>As the meteors cour&s;e the &s;ky,</L>
<L>Gleaming &s;words fla&s;h round the throng,</L>
<L>And, as thro' the gloom they fly,</L>
<L>Light th' embattled ho&s;t along;</L>
<L>Firm and clo&s;e we lead our band</L>
<L>Where the fertile region lies,</L>
<L>Then, di&s;per&s;ing, &s;weep the land</L>
<L>De&s;tin'd for THE TARTARS' PRIZE.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHORUS&mdash;HORDE.</SPEAKER>
<L>Worlds of wealth, and worlds of wives,</L>
<L>Are the hardy TARTARS' PRIZE.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ITHORAK.</SPEAKER>
<L>Tho' we deem the world our prey,</L>
<L>Loya<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word">, martial truth,</L>
<L>When our &s;words have won their way,</L>
<L><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 span"> Tartar youth;</L>
<L>Choice of &s;poil, as fir&s;t in fight,</L>
<L>With <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> gallant chieftain lies,</L>
<L>Then, till Honour have her right,</L>
<L>Sacred be the TARTARS' PRIZE.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="52" REF="51">
<SPEAKER>CHORUS.&mdash;HORDE.</SPEAKER>
<L>Worlds of wealth, and worlds of wives,</L>
<L>Are the hardy TARTARS' PRIZE.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Japhis.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well &s;aid, well &s;aid, he's a noble cap|tain, and &s;hall have all the booty, if he plea&s;es.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<STAGE>Flouri&s;h and Shouts.</STAGE>
<STAGE>Enter KERA KHAN, and Tartars.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hola! Lovin&s;ki is &s;ecured.&mdash;Why &s;tand you idle here?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Japhis.</SPEAKER>
<P>Becau&s;e you &s;tation'd us in this wing till farther orders.&mdash;We &s;hould be glad enough to be bu&s;y.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Away then, fini&s;h your work; &s;pike all the cannon, to&s;s the brands round, blow up the foundation of this ru&s;&s;ian's den, and tell my father's &s;pirit he's reveng'd.&mdash;To work&mdash;I'll take this quarter.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Excunt Tartars, others remain.</STAGE>
<STAGE>Enter LODOISKA, and Prince LUPAUSKI.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodoi&s;ka.</SPEAKER>
<P>O, &s;ave us, &s;ave us,&mdash;&s;natch me from the power of Lovin&s;ki.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Prince.</SPEAKER>
<P>Tartars! Great Heaven, to what are we re&s;erv'd?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Compo&s;e your&s;elf, my lovely girl;
<PB N="53" REF="52">di&s;mi&s;s your terrors.&mdash;This is a prize!&mdash;Here's my &s;hare of the booty.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Japhis.</SPEAKER>
<P>I thought &s;o.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Prince.</SPEAKER>
<P>Since we are fallen into the&s;e hands, my child, we mu&s;t &s;ubmit to death, or &s;lavery.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Slavery, death, any thing, is Heaven to Lovin&s;ki.&mdash; Oh, if you are men, &s;pare my dear Father, &s;pare a Poli&s;h youth,&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Bright beauty of the world, only pronounce your wi&s;hes, and command us.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Generous conquerors!&mdash;Vouch&s;afe then to give this young man freedom, to &s;et my father and my&s;elf upon our road to War&s;aw, and&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan.</SPEAKER>
<P>For your Father, and the youth you &s;peak of, they have free leave to choo&s;e their path;&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan.</SPEAKER>
<P>But you, victorious captive, you mu&s;t go with me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Heavens and Earth!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Prince.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thee! follow thee, Tartar!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Old man, I am providing for her happine&s;s.&mdash;Fine women never complain of us Tartars; when once &s;he knows us, &s;he'll never wi&s;h to leave us&mdash;I have no time to lo&s;e&mdash;Come, be quick, bear her away.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="54" REF="53">
Enter COUNT FLORESKI, breaking from the Poli&s;h Officers.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Off, &s;laves, or I will da&s;h you piecemeal.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Floreski!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! valiant Tartar, do we meet again?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan.</SPEAKER>
<P>My friend!&mdash;Why do I find you here, &s;pite of the caution I la&s;t night gave you?&mdash; Your life might have paid the forfeit of your ra&s;h|ne&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>That villain Lovinski &s;eiz'd, and de|tain'd us;&mdash;But could I, could I, have le&s;t my Lodoiska?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, &s;he you were wildly wander|ing after?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here,&mdash;this, this is my love, my deare&s;t Lodoiska.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Drawing his Scymetar.)</STAGE>
<P>Hold&mdash; What's to be done?&mdash;Your love? your Lodoiska? She's mine, mine by a conqueror's right.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>A conqueror's right!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan.</SPEAKER>
<P>By a conqueror's right;&mdash;and I exert it thus.&mdash;Take her, &s;he's your's.&mdash;You gave me life once, I have &s;av'd yours a &s;econd time.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Complete thy work; obtain for me the con&s;ent of her Father,&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Father!&mdash;Haven't I re&s;ign'd my right to you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(To Lupau&s;ki)</STAGE>
<P>O, Sir, make not &s;idelity
<PB N="55" REF="54">to his Prince a crime in him; think what he has &s;uffer'd for me; think what we owe him here; re|member the promi&s;e you once gave him;&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Alarum.</STAGE>
<STAGE>Enter KAJAH, TAMURI, CAMAZIN, and Tartars.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kajah.</SPEAKER>
<P>To arms, to arms.&mdash;Lovinski's re&s;cued, the ca&s;tle's blazing, they've &s;eiz'd the ramparts, he's at their head.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, we mu&s;t conquer him again then, that's all.&mdash;Follow me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now for revenge and Lodoiska!&mdash;Give me a &s;word, a &s;word.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter VARBEL.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Holla! and me another&mdash;My dun|geon's as hot as a furnace. Give me a &s;word; I'd as lie&s; be kill'd in a battle, as &s;tay there to be roa&s;ted alive.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan.</SPEAKER>
<P>During the combat, we'll place this lovely creature in &s;afety with her father in yonder tower.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Varbel.</SPEAKER>
<P>I wi&s;h you'd place me along with 'em.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Prince.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;corn to owe thee any thing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ob&s;tinate man!&mdash;We'll &s;ave you then again&s;t your will.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>Will you expo&s;e her life?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Prince.</SPEAKER>
<P>My child! My child!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, come, my father.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="56" REF="55">
Shouts, Drams, Trumpets, and Cannon.</STAGE>
<P>AN ENGAGEMENT COMMENCES BETWEEN THE POLANDERS and the TARTARS;</P>
<P>The Tartars having &s;tormed the Ca&s;tle, which they fire in various places, the battlements and towers fall in the mid&s;t of loud explo&s;ions.</P>
<P>LUPAUSKI and LODOISKA</P>
<P>Are di&s;cover'd in a blazing tower;</P>
<P><HI>FLORESKI</HI> ru&s;hes through the flames, and re&s;cues them.</P>
<P>During this action</P>
<P>LOVINSKI and KERA KHAN</P>
<P>meet hand to hand, and, after a de&s;perate conflict, the Baron is killed.</P>
<STAGE>The Tartars are victorious&mdash;Loud &s;houts of victory.</STAGE>
<SP>
<PB N="57" REF="56">
<SPEAKER>Kera Khan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Since the&s;e are &s;afe, and my injuries fully aveng'd by Lovinski's fall, I pardon his de|luded followers.&mdash;Set your captives at liberty;&mdash; This &s;hall be to all a day of triumph and joy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lodo.</SPEAKER>
<P>And now, my father,&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Prince.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your reque&s;t upbraids me, my daughter. &mdash;Come hither, Count.&mdash;The only proof I now ask of your obedience is to love him truly&mdash; Take her, Floreski; you have indeed de&s;erv'd her.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter CAPTIVES, POLANDERS, &amp;c.</STAGE>
<Q><TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>FINALE.</HEAD>
<STAGE>LODOISKA, COUNT, and All the Characters.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LODOISKA.</SPEAKER>
<L>O, happy hour! what bli&s;s I feel!</L>
<L>A parent does my choice approve,</L>
<L>And deigns to put the &s;acred &s;eal</L>
<L>Of duty to an act of love.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHORUS.</SPEAKER>
<L>Huzza! rejoice!&mdash;let cheerful &s;trains re&s;ound,</L>
<L>And echo &s;well the pealing carol round,</L>
<L>Till the wide world a mighty chorus rai&s;e</L>
<L>To valour's triumph, and to beauty's prai&s;e.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="58" REF="57">
<SPEAKER>COUNT.</SPEAKER>
<L>My joys in thee, my life, were poor,</L>
<L>My gratitude to you but weak,</L>
<L>If language had an equal pow'r</L>
<L>The tran&s;ports of my &s;oul to &s;peak.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHORUS.</SPEAKER>
<L>Huzza! rejoice!&mdash;let cheerful &s;trains re&s;ound,</L>
<L>And echo &s;well the pealing carol round,</L>
<L>Till the wide world a mighty chorus rai&s;e</L>
<L>To valour's triumph, and to beauty's prai&s;e.</L>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
</DIV2>
<TRAILER>FINIS.</TRAILER>
